elements.content: Three succinate−metal coordination polymers have been synthesized and characterized. The structure of Co(dmbpy)(H2O)2(C4H4O4) (dmbpy = 4,4‘-dimethyl-2,2‘-bipyridine, C4H4O4 = succinate; 1) contains zipperlike chains, which are constructed of Co(II), dmbpy, H2O, and bridging succinates. The structure of two isomorphous 2-D compounds, M(dpdo)(H2O)2(C4H4O4) (M = Zn (2) or Mn (3), dpdo = 4,4‘-dipyridyl N,N‘-dioxide), consists of grid networks of succinate−metal chains linked by dpdo.

elements.content: Functional coordination polymers consisting of metal ions connected together by di- or polycarboxylates are of great interest because of their ability to show novel topological characteristics and potential applications in many areas. Among these carboxylates, the succinate ligand has aroused extensive attention, and many extended coordination polymers of it have been reported. Noteworthy examples of these polymers are the interpenetrating (10,3) 3-D net [Na3Cd5(C4H4O4)6X] (X = Cl, Br), [Ni7(C4H4O4)4(OH)6(H2O)3]·7H2O, which has remarkable void volumes and can reversibly re-absorb water molecules, Ni7(C4H4O4)6(OH)2(H2O)2]·2H2O, the 3-D succinato-pillared coordination polymers Mn5(OH)2(C4H4O4)4 and Cd3(OH)2(C4H4O4)2, the 3-D rare earth polymer [Pr(H2O)]2[C4H4O4]3·H2O, and an effective Lewis acid catalyst Sc2(C4H4O4)2.5(OH). By introduction of some organic chelate ligands, several lower dimensional structures have also been found. We have recently prepared a new 2-D 4,82 network Cu4(pmo)4(C4H4O4)2·H2O (Hpmo = 2-pyridinemethanol). Here, we describe the crystal structures of molecular zippers Co(dmbpy)(H2O)2(C4H4O4) (dmbpy = 4,4‘-dimethyl-2,2‘-bipyridine, C4H4O4 = succinate; 1) and two isomorphous 2-D grid coordination polymers M(dpdo)(H2O)2(C4H4O4) (M = Zn (2) or Mn (3), dpdo = 4,4‘-dipyridyl N,N‘-dioxide).
elements.clean_text:
Introduction

Functional coordination polymers consisting of metal ions connected together by di- or polycarboxylates are of great interest because of their ability to show novel topological characteristics and potential applications in many areas. Among these carboxylates, the succinate ligand has aroused extensive attention, and many extended coordination polymers of it have been reported. Noteworthy examples of these polymers are the interpenetrating (10,3) 3-D net [Na3Cd5(C4H4O4)6X] (X = Cl, Br), [Ni7(C4H4O4)4(OH)6(H2O)3]⋅7H2O, which has remarkable void volumes and can reversibly re-absorb water molecules, Ni7(C4H4O4)6(OH)2(H2O)2]⋅2H2O, the 3-D succinato-pillared coordination polymers Mn5(OH)2(C4H4O4)4 and Cd3(OH)2(C4H4O4)2, the 3-D rare earth polymer [Pr(H2O)]2[C4H4O4]3⋅H2O, and an effective Lewis acid catalyst Sc2(C4H4O4)2.5(OH). By introduction of some organic chelate ligands, several lower dimensional structures have also been found. We have recently prepared a new 2-D 4,82 network Cu4(pmo)4(C4H4O4)2⋅H2O (Hpmo = 2-pyridinemethanol). Here, we describe the crystal structures of molecular zippers Co(dmbpy)(H2O)2(C4H4O4) (dmbpy = 4,4‘-dimethyl-2,2‘-bipyridine, C4H4O4 = succinate; 1) and two isomorphous 2-D grid coordination polymers M(dpdo)(H2O)2(C4H4O4) (M = Zn (2) or Mn (3), dpdo = 4,4‘-dipyridyl N,N‘-dioxide).

elements.content: Materials. Dmbpy and dpdo were purchased from Aldrich Company. All other reagents were commercially available and used without further purification. Elemental analyses (C, H, N) were carried out by using a Perkin-Elmer Elemental Analyzer 2400. The IR spectra were recorded on a BIO-RAD FTS 160 FT-IR spectrophotometer as KBr pellets in the 4000−400 cm-1 region. The thermogravimetric analysis was made by a LT-1 model thermobalance under a N2 atmosphere.

Experimental Section

 Materials. Dmbpy and dpdo were purchased from Aldrich Company. All other reagents were commercially available and used without further purification. Elemental analyses (C, H, N) were carried out by using a Perkin-Elmer Elemental Analyzer 2400. The IR spectra were recorded on a BIO-RAD FTS 160 FT-IR spectrophotometer as KBr pellets in the 4000-400 cm-1 region. The thermogravimetric analysis was made by a LT-1 model thermobalance under a N2 atmosphere.

elements.content: Preparation of Co(dmbpy)(H 2 O) 2 (C 4 H 4 O 4 ) (1). Succinic acid (0.1181 g, 1 mmol) was dissolved in a solution of NaOH (0.008 g, 2 mmol) in H2O (4 mL), and the resulting solution was added to a solution of CoAc2·4H2O (0.2491 g, 1 mmol) and dmdpy (0.1842 g, 1 mmol) in 4 mL of methanol/water. The mixture was stirred for 10 min and then filtered. Upon slow evaporation of the filtrate at room temperature, well-shaped red crystals of 1 were obtained. They were filtered off, washed with a small amount of water, and dried in air. The yield is 65%. Anal. Calcd. for C16H20N2O6Co:  C, 48.62; H, 5.10; N, 7.09. Found:  C, 48.59; H, 5.05; N, 7.31%. IR (KBr disk) cm-1:  νas(COO-) 1614, νs(COO-) 1395 cm-1.

elements.content: Three coordination polymers 1−3 are insoluble in water and slightly soluble in methanol and acetone. All these compounds are air stable and can retain their structural integrity at room temperature for a considerable length of time. The thermogravimetric analysis of the crystalline samples showed a weight loss in the temperature range 105−130 °C, corresponding to two water molecules (8.95%, 8.58%, and 9.42% for 1−3; calculated:  9.10%, 8.87%, and 9.11%, respectively). The anhydrous compounds began to decompose at 320, 345, and 340 °C, respectively.

elements.content: Crystal Data Collection and Refinement. The diffraction experiments were carried out on a Bruker AXS SMART CCD diffractometer at −50 °C. The SMART program was used for collecting frames of data, indexing reflection, and determination of lattice parameters, the SAINT13 program for integration of the intensity of reflections and scaling, the SADABS program for absorption correction, and the SHELXTL program for space group and structure determination, and least-squares refinements on F 2. Metal atoms in each complex were located from E-maps. The other non-hydrogen atoms were located in successive difference Fourier syntheses. The final refinement was performed by full matrix least-squares. In all three compounds, H atoms of water molecules were located in the difference electron density map and refined isotropically. All the other hydrogen atoms were located by geometric placing. Selected crystallographic data and refinement details are displayed in Table .

Complex Co(dmbpy)(H 2 O) 2 (C 4 H 4 O 4 ) (1). The Co(II) ion octahedron in complex 1 is tetragonally compressed from O h symmetry with the two N atoms of dmbpy ligands (Co(1)−N(1), 2.116(2); Co(1)−N(2), 2.107(2) Å) and the two O atoms of coordinate aqua molecules (Co(1)−O(5), 2.154(2); Co(1)−O(6), 2.127(2) Å) in the equatorial plane. Two carboxylate oxygen atoms of two succinate ligands (Co(1)−O(1), 2.055(2); Co(1)−O(3A), 2.065(2) Å) occupy the axial positions. Figure shows an ORTEP diagram of the first coordination sphere of the Co(II) site and atom labeling. The succinate ligands bridge each pair of adjacent Co(II) atoms to produce a chain running along the a axis with a distance of 8.42 Å between each pair of Co(II) atoms. The approximately perpendicular orientation of dmbpy ligands allows pairing of two centrosymmetrically related single-stranded chains to generate a double-stranded zipperlike chain along the a-axis allowing for aromatic π−π stacking interactions between the bpy pairs. Such zipperlike chain structures are notably common biochemically, but so far, few examples of zipperlike coordination polymer compounds have been reported. The dihedral angle of the pyridyl groups in each dmbpy is 4.53°. The face-to-face distance between the paired bpy rings is about 4.2 Å, indicating a moderate aromatic π−π stacking interaction. The distance between the two strands of the zipper is about 7.37 Å. The packing of the complex along the b axis is shown in Figure . A close inspection of the crystal structure information shows that two adjacent zipper molecules are linked by interzipper hydrogen bonds between coordinated water oxygen atoms and uncoordinated carboxylate oxygen atoms of succinate ligands (O(5)···O(2 i ), 2.807 Å; O(5)−H(5b)···O(2 i ), 170.4°; O(6)···O(4 ii ), 2.758 Å; O(6)−H(6c)···O(4 ii ), 176.9°. Symmetry code i = −x, −y + 1, −z − 1; ii = −x, −y + 1, −z − 1) leading to a 2-D sheet. However, no strong interactions have been observed between adjacent layers (Figure ).

elements.content: Complexes M(dpdo)(H 2 O) 2 (C 4 H 4 O 4 ) (M = Zn (2) or Mn (3)). Since the manganese derivative 3 is isomorphous with 2, only the structure of the zinc derivative 2 is described here. The coordination sphere of the zinc(II) site in 2 is defined by two oxygen atoms of coordinate aqua molecules (Zn(1)−O(4), 2.110(1) Å) and two carboxylate oxygen atoms of two succinate ligands (Zn(1)−O(2), 2.028(1) Å) in the equatorial plane and two oxygen donors of dpdo ligands (Zn(1)−O(1), 2.189(1) Å) in the apical position leading to a slightly distorted ZnO6 octahedron. The Zn ions are bridged by succinate ligand along the [001] direction, yielding a linear chain with a distance of 9.823 Å between two adjacent Zn ions. These adjacent chains are further linked through dpdo, leading to a 2-D grid sheet in the [011] plane with an interlayer separation of 5.4 Å, in which the dpdo adopts a trans connection fashion (Figure ). The distance between two zinc atoms bridged by dpdo is 11.907 Å. The two pyridyl groups of the dpdo ligand are completely coplanar, and it is nearly perpendicular to the 2-D sheet. No significant π−π stacking interactions are found between these dpdo molecules. These adjacent 2-D sheets are further connected through hydrogen bonds between the coordinated water molecules and bridging dpdo ligand or uncoordinated carboxylate oxygen, leading to a 3-D structure motif as illustrated in Figure (O(4)···O(3i):  2.663 Å; O(4)···O(1ii):  2.739 Å. Symmetry code:  i:  −x, −y, −z; ii:  x−1, y, z). Selected bond lengths and angles for compounds 1−3 are collected in Table .

Three novel coordination polymers assembled by bridging succinate ligand have been prepared and characterized. Compound 1 consists of a zipperlike structure constructed through π−π interactions, which extends to a 2-D sheet through hydrogen bonding. Compounds 2 and 3 form 2-D grid sheets and give 3-D networks through interlayer hydrogen bonding.
elements.clean_text:
Conclusions

Three novel coordination polymers assembled by bridging succinate ligand have been prepared and characterized. Compound 1 consists of a zipperlike structure constructed through π-π interactions, which extends to a 2-D sheet through hydrogen bonding. Compounds 2 and 3 form 2-D grid sheets and give 3-D networks through interlayer hydrogen bonding.

Preparation of Co(dmbpy)(H 2 O) 2 (C 4 H 4 O 4 ) (1). Succinic acid (0.1181 g, 1 mmol) was dissolved in a solution of NaOH (0.008 g, 2 mmol) in H2O (4 mL), and the resulting solution was added to a solution of CoAc2·4H2O (0.2491 g, 1 mmol) and dmdpy (0.1842 g, 1 mmol) in 4 mL of methanol/water. The mixture was stirred for 10 min and then filtered. Upon slow evaporation of the filtrate at room temperature, well-shaped red crystals of 1 were obtained. They were filtered off, washed with a small amount of water, and dried in air. The yield is 65%. Anal. Calcd. for C16H20N2O6Co:  C, 48.62; H, 5.10; N, 7.09. Found:  C, 48.59; H, 5.05; N, 7.31%. IR (KBr disk) cm-1:  νas(COO-) 1614, νs(COO-) 1395 cm-1.

Preparation of Zn(dpdo)(H 2 O) 2 (C 4 H 4 O 4 ) (2). Succinic acid (0.1181 g, 1 mmol) was dissolved in a solution of NaOH (0.008 g, 2 mmol) in H2O (4 mL), and the resulting solution was added to a solution of ZnAc2·2H2O (0.2195 g, 1 mmol) and dpdo·H2O (0.2062 g, 1 mmol) in 2 mL of water. The mixture was stirred for 10 min and then filtered. Upon slow evaporation of the filtrate at room temperature, well-shaped pale-yellow crystals of 2 were obtained. They were filtered off, washed with a small amount of water, and dried in air. The yield is 58%. Anal. Calcd. for C14H16N2O8Zn:  C, 41.45; H, 3.98; N, 6.91. Found:  C, 41.65; H, 3.84; N, 6.75%. IR (KBr disk) cm-1: νas(COO-) 1611, νs(COO-) 1340 cm-1.

Preparation of Mn(dpdo)(H 2 O) 2 (C 4 H 4 O 4 ) (3). The compound 3 was synthesized using the same procedure for 2 but from MnCl2·6H2O. The crystals obtained are red, and the yield is 56%. Anal. Calcd. for C14H16N2O8Mn:  C, 42.55; H, 4.08; N, 7.09. Found:  C, 42.37; H, 3.84; N, 7.13%. IR (KBr disk) cm-1:  νas(COO-) 1609, νs(COO-) 1398 cm-1.

cln_elements.content: Three coordination polymers 1−3 are insoluble in water and slightly soluble in methanol and acetone. All these compounds are air stable and can retain their structural integrity at room temperature for a considerable length of time. The thermogravimetric analysis of the crystalline samples showed a weight loss in the temperature range 105−130 °C, corresponding to two water molecules (8.95%, 8.58%, and 9.42% for 1−3; calculated:  9.10%, 8.87%, and 9.11%, respectively). The anhydrous compounds began to decompose at 320, 345, and 340 °C, respectively.
